{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0d81759f-59e0-4448-b03e-a7e11cfeb02a","content":"Here's the correct skip attribute for each framework:\n\n**MSTest**\n```csharp\n[Ignore(\"Reason for skipping\")]\n```\n\n**xUnit (v2)**\n```csharp\n[Fact(Skip = \"Reason for skipping\")]\n[Theory(Skip = \"Reason for skipping\")]\n```\n\n**xUnit (v3)**\nSame as v2, but also supports runtime skip via `Assert.Skip(\"reason\")` inside the test body.\n\n**NUnit**\n```csharp\n[Ignore(\"Reason for skipping\")]\n```\n\n**TUnit**\n```csharp\n[Skip(\"Reason for skipping\")]\n```\n\nAll frameworks require or support a reason string. The skipped tests will appear in results as \"skipped\" or \"inconclusive\" rather than passed/failed, so they won't be silently lost.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d7805aea-21ca-4335-b039-188d11909a39","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about skip/ignore attributes across MSTest, xUnit, NUnit, and TUnit. This is a straightforward reference question about test framework APIs. I can answer this directly from knowledge without needing to invoke any tools or skills.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":277,"requestId":"0442:CB29E:1FFAB52:23F025B:69E81E62"},"id":"793b0172-6f35-4240-8aa7-71f592d3a96e","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:03:37.187Z","parentId":"fcc8a857-6c8c-4a55-872a-4fdbf75c86b4"}
